15 pounds Mttriato of\nPotash per hundred.\nComplete fertilizer means best crops and biggest\nprolt.\nEvery agent sells phosphate. Few carry Potash In stock.\nArrange for Potash now. Potash it profit.\nS.nd for NcwFarmtr't Note Rook, eont.lniniirti\nabout Mil, erupt, manures and f.ruluait. Madtu free.\nGERMAN KALI WORKS, Monadnock Bldjf., Chicago\nfiuua St. Alttats, 04.-I2H tulto UUr.\nU. S. SEIZES ARMS\nFREIGHT LISTED AS VARIOUS\nSORTS OF MERCHANDISE.\nINFORMED BY CUBAN MINISTER\nGovernment Had Not Known Before\nof Any Trouble Brewing,\nIn Island,\nNew York l'xposuro of n pro\njected revolution camo Saturday\nwhen tho steamship Seguaranca of\nthe Ward lino was hold up by special\nagents of tho treasury department.\nTen thousand lounds of ammunition,\nwhich hntl been Intended for agents\nof tho revolutionary party at Santia\ngo do Cuba, woro confiscated.\nTho descent was made upon tho\nSegunranca Jurt when preparations\nwero being made for starting her upon\nher way to Cuba. Tho oppearnnce of\ntho treasury mun caused a stir among\nthe pnssengors, who wero unablo to\nunderstand why tho unexpected vis\nitors held up tho ship and overturned\neverything aboard In the unoxplnlnod\nsearch which they proceoded lo make\nThat tho ammunition was seized\nby the federal officials Is duo to In\nformation given to tho secretary of\ntho treasury by tho Cuban minister\nnt Washington, Oonzulo do Quesada.\nUntil ho made the announcement that\ncontraband goodB for tho rebel party\nwere bolng shipped to his country\nnothing was known about any at\ntempt to fomont trouble there. Threo\nhours were required to comploto tho\nsoarch. After six hours' delay tho\nvessel was permitted to go on hor\nway.\nWhen tho ammunition was flnnlly\nbrought to light tho conimnndor of tho\nvessel and tho agents of tho company\nwero dumfotinded. Ono largo box bad\nbeen shipped as a piano, and others\nwere snld to contain various sorts of\nmerchandise.\nSUFFRAGETTE DEMONSTRATION.\n10,000\nWomen\nof\nWill Parade Streets\nLondon.\nLondon The suffragettes Sat\nurday afternoon held tho most\nImposing demonstration they have\nyet attempted whon 10,000 women\nfrom every part of tho Prrltlsh Isles\nand from tho colonies, tho United\nStntos and aovoral of tho Kuropean\ncountrlos will march from tho\nThnmos embankment to Albert hall,\nwhere they will hold a meeting. Fea\ntures of tho procession will bo S00\nbanners symbolical of woman's\nsphoio and women famous lu tho\nworld's history.\nMllllcent Garrett Fawcctt, LU D.,\nwidow of tho Hlght Hon. Henry Faw\ncutt, was lo have led tho procession,\nbut as a compliment to her America:\nco-workers, she has resigned tho placa\nof honor to two delegates from -Alio\nT'nited States, Dr. Anna Shaw and\nMiss Lucy J. Anthony, who will bo In\ntho first carriage.\nKILLS TWO AND HIMSELF.\nMan In a Jealous Rage Kills Friend\nand Landlady.\nDenver, Col. In jealous rage\nFriday night, Charles E. livers\nshot and killed Mrs. May K. Horen,\nlandlady of a rooming house, followed\nthis up by murdering Edward Smith,\nand then followed himself. llyers\nand Smith wero lodgers at tho room\ning house conducted by Mrs. lloron.\nSmith was a roccnt arrival, having\ncomo at the solicitation of his friends\nllyers. Thursday night ho mado ac\ncusations against Mrs. Horen and\nSmith, and as a result was ordered\nfrom tho hout.o by tho woman. Friday\nnight he waj granted nn Interview\nwith Mrs. Hoien, and tho shooting fol\nlowed. Mrs. Horen camo hero two\nyears ago from Howard, Kan. A year\nago she was divorced from her hus\nband, J. V. Horen, who still rosldos\nwith two of their children at Howard.\nCONSCIENCE FUND INCREASED.\nMan Returns Money Taken from Gov\nernment Years Ago.\nWashington, D. C. Secretary\nCortelyon has received In an en-\nvclopo, postmarked Jorsey city, a\nconscience contribution of $S,000,\nwhich has been turned Into tho con\nsclenco fund of tho troasury. in an\nunsigned letter tho gender says that\nmany years ago that ho and another\nman took a considerable sum of\nmoney belonging to tho govornmont\nand that this $8,000 makes a total of\n40,000, or fourfold tho amount orig\ninally taken by hlmsolf. This sum,\nho says, has beon returned to tho\ntreasury from tlmo to time, covering\na period of several years.\nGlass Company Bankrupt.\nContralla, 111. Tho Allison glass\nworks of this city, employing\n300 men, Friday filed a petition\nIn bankruptcy with tho federal court\nTho llabllltios nro given as $1S 1,000,\nwith assets of 1150,000.\nStarved In Car of Potatoes,\nNow York Crazed from want\nof food and wntor, Cheater A\nO'Connoll, a machinist of Datf: Ueach\nwas rescuod from a freight car In\ntho Harlem yards Friday and taken\nto Lincoln hospital, where It was said\nthat ho mlKht dto. O'Connell wa\nworking In Jacksonville, Fla., aud\nlosing his Job, crawled into a freight\ncar laden with potatoes, to moko his\nway back to New York. While ho\nwas asleep in the car tho door was\nlocked and tho cur started north-\nSlayer of Four Denied Rehearing.\nAlbany, N. Y. Charles II. Hog\nors, convicted of tho murdor of\nFred It. Olnoy of Walklll, Orange\ncounty, was deniod a new trial In a\ndecision handed down by the court\nof appeals Friday. Rogers was ac\ncused of murdering Fred and Wllls\nOlnoy, brothers, tholr housekeeper,\nMrs. Georgia Itigcrlck, and the lattor's\ndaughter Allco, C years old. Uobborj\nwas tho motive for the crime. Hog\nors fled, b was arrostcd months oft\nenvard In Jlfornla.\nFAIR DEAL NEEDED\nFIRST\nREQUISITE FOR RETURN\nOF PROSPERITY.\nArtiVlelal Methods of No Avail While\nthe Republican Policy of Protect\ning Trusts and Corporations\nContinues In Force.\nTwo elements nro at work trying to\ncreate prosperity, nnd both acem to\nomannto from the same source. Cer\ntain Wall street Interests have been\nforcing up tho prlco of securities for\nsome weeks until railroad nnd Indus\ntrial stocks nro higher than before tho\npanic occurred. Then wo havo tho\nNational Prosperity association going\nUp so far as to sot Juno 1 for the birth\nof the now prosperity thnt Is to en\nvelop us with n golden mantle. Tho\nplan seems to be to boost stocks In\nWall street so that thu railroads can\nborrow moro money, which from tho\nffarrlman-llockofellcr point of view\na suro sign of prosperity.\nTho manufacturers nro to do their\npart by starting up nil the factories\non full time and, of course, selling the\nproducts nt full prices.\nWhether this hotbed process of pro\nducing prosperity will work can, of\ncourse, bo only surmised, but ns tho\nprimary heat furnished by tho stock\nmarket manipulators does not seem\nto have warmed up the lambs to tho\nnecessary enthusiasm, prices aro or\nlatlc and Inclined to sag. Tho lambs\nhavo beon shorn too lately ami closely\nto bo expected to show much enthusi\nasm until their fleeces havo had tlmo\nto grow enough to cover their naked\nness. Thoro Is no doubt that all tho tariff-\nprotected trusts can stnrt production\non a largo scrJe, but whether tho con\nsumers enn pay the high prices neces-\nsary for this hotbed brand of pros\nperity is moro than doubtful. To over\nstock tho mnrkot with manufactured\ngoods that many people In their pov\nerty through lack of employment can\nnot pay for, will hardly help matters\nunless the trusts aro prepared to re\nduce prices and thus stimulate demand.\nAs tho nopubllcnn congress has .re\nfused to reform tho tariff, tho tariff\nprotected trusts still have tho power\nto collect their share of tho tariff tax;\nand Judging from tho notion of tho\nsleol trust, the beet (rust, tho sugar\ntrust and many others, In determin\ning not to reduce prices, they evident\nly do not Intend to dlvldo their pros\nperity with their customers\nTho people generally must havo\nmoney In their pockets before prosper\nity returns. Confidence Is a child of\nlmv growth, and until confidence Is\nrestored it is much to bo feared that\nprosperity, nourished by tho corpora\ntions for their own selfish ends, will\nhardly bo deep enough to reach the\nhomes of the people.\nWho has conlldonco In any pros\nperity for the people from Wall street\nmanipulators?\nCan prosperity come to tho peoplo\nby paying the trusts moro than they\ncharge foreigners?\nWho can havo any confidence that\nRepublican policies will produce pros\nperity since the panic, and with tho\nbusiness of the country still at low\nebb?\nEveryone wants prosperity, certain\nly for hlmsolf, and may be depended\nupon to do what he can to secure It\nIf tho peoplo can secure a fair deol\nthey will bo prosperous, but with the\nRepublican policy of protecting t In\ntrusts and corporations In plundering\nthem by high prices and still higher\nrates for transportation, the brand\nof prosperity that has been and is to\nbe handed out. Is of tho Dead-sea ap\nple variety that crumbles at tho touch\nof Investigation. Please keep cool\nand give tho people a chance to re-\nuperate. Under bad laws, and tho\nstand-pat policy that our Republican\ngovernors have forced us to boar, tho\ngrowth of better times will bo slow\nfor the people, though tho trusts and\ncorporations should soon nourish us\ntho green hay tiee.\nThe Trusts and High Prices.\nRut If capital and labor are pursu\ning a right course, it Is not so evident\nthat thoso trusts which, under tin iff\nprotection, cap advance the prices of\nthe necessaries of life ns they sec fit,\nare acting In good faith with thu con\nsumers of this country.\nTho. trusts obtained their power fur\n.-onsolldnttng compotlng concerns with\nthe implied understanding that they\ncould thereby glvo tho people mure\nreasonable prices. In the days nf\ncompetition, after a panic, tin- cost\nof living was reduced because com\npetitors made prices lower there\nwore no \"gontlemen's agreements.\"\nNow, with trusts wielding nn almost\ntyrannical power, tho peoplo ilnd\nprices soaring Instead of being low\nered In depressed tlnios.\nTho farmers cannot be blamed for\ntho exorbitant prices of beef, eggs,\nvegetables and many nrtlcles that go\ninto cold sttirngo. They do not re\ncotvo tho f.tney prices which the tin\nfortunato consumers must pay. The\ntrusts seo that no ono bonefits besides\nthemselves. Boston Olobo.\nA Vicious Record,\nCongress has passed the $1,000,000,\n000 mark, thus breaking nil records\nfor oxtrnagnnt appropriations, and\nthis In the faco of a probable deficit\nfor the next fiscal year In tho income\nof tho government of $160,000,000.\nHnvo tho Republican leaders become\nreckless that thoy thus spend tho peo\nple's money In theso hard times, with\nout thought of tho extra taxos or\nmoro bonds that will havo to bo Im\nposed to meet their wastoful expendi\ntures? Do thoy know their political\ndoom Is sealed? The voter that does\nnot rebuke his representative, and tho\nsenators from his stnto, that voted\nfor theso enormous expropriations,\ndeserves to bo plundered by politi\ncians nnd trusts to tho end of his\ndays. The record shows that tho gag\nrulcB wore adopted nnd supported by\nall the Republicans on purposo to pro\nvent tho Democrats from offering\namendments to roduco tho extrava\nganco.\nAn Oratorio of Memory.\nHo'mo should bo an oratorio of mom\nor.v. slnglns: to nil our nftor-llfe melo\ndies and harmonics of old-romemborod\nloy. IJeecher.\nONE WOMAN'S ENDURANCE.\nSouthern- Woman Suffers\nWithout Complaint.\nTorturo\nRocked and torn with torrlflc pains,\nnightly' annoyed by kidney Irregulari\nties, Mrs. A. b.\nPayne, of 801 Third\nnvo, So,, Columbus,\nMiss., suffered for\nyears. Sho says:\n\"The pnlns In my\nback, sides and loins\nworo so terrible thnt\nI often smothered a\nscream. Every movo\nMy test was broken by\nmeant agony\na troublesome weakness nnd the bo\ncrotlons Feomed to burn like acid. I\nwas in nn awful condition and doctors\ndid not scorn to help 1110. Doan's Kid\nney Pills benefitted mo from tho first\nand soon made mo a strong nnd\nhealthy woman.\"\nFor snlo by all dealers. HO cents a\nbox. Fostor-MIIburn Co., Buffalo, N.Y.\nSTRONGON THE PROPRI